data.enText: used to say that sth cannot be avoided
The number of places available is necessarily limited.
data.chText: 可录学生的名额不可避免地很有限。

data.enText: used to say that sth is possibly true but not definitely or always true
The more expensive articles are not necessarily better.
data.chText: 较贵的东西不见得就较好。
最大的不一定是最好的。

tr: in such a manner as could not be otherwise

example: we are necessarily bound for federalism in Europe

example.ex: Anger is not necessarily the most useful or acceptable reaction to such events...
example.tran: 对于这种事，发火不见得是最有用或最能被接受的反应。

example.ex: Speed and safety are not necessarily incompatible...
example.tran: 速度和安全未必不相容。

example.ex: A higher fee does not necessarily mean a better course.
example.tran: 收费更高并不意味着课程就一定更好。

defx.def: If you reply 'Not necessarily', you mean that what has just been said or suggested may not be true.

gramarinfo.label: with neg, ADV group, ADV before v

value.def: If you say that something is not necessarily the case, you mean that it may not be the case or is not always the case.

example.ex: The most desirable properties necessarily command astonishingly high prices...
example.tran: 最值得拥有的财产必然要价不菲。

example.ex: Tourism is an industry that has a necessarily close connection with governments.
example.tran: 旅游业是与政府有着必然的密切联系的产业。

value.def: If you say that something necessarily happens or is the case, you mean that it has to happen or be the case and cannot be any different.
